# *Decision making in C or conditionals* #

We all make some simple decisions like, which clothes to where to very important decisions like chosing our life partner in our life.

Now, the question is how computer make decisions?

Yes, here comes the importance of decision making in C or any other programing language.
In C we have different types of decision making statements.

for example

1. if statement
2. if else statement
3. Nested if statement
4. if else if
5. switch statements

if statement

syntax:-

if(condition)

{
statement1;
statement2;

}

if the condition in the bracket returns true then the statements in the braces get executed. 
if the condition returns false then the compiler skip the statements writen in the braces.

for example-

int A=13,B=10;

if(A>B)
{
  printf("A>B");
  
 }
 printf("Done");
 
 in this example 13 and 10 are assigned to the variable A and B respectively.
 The condition A>B  returns true since 13>10. so the output of the program will be.
 
 Output:- A>B Done.
 
 if else statement

syntax:-

if(condition)

{
ifstatement1;
ifstatement2;

}
else
{
elsestatement1;
elsestatement2;
}


In this type of statements if the condition inside the bracket returns true then the statements in the braces get executed. 
if the condition returns false then the compiler skip the ifstatements and execute the elsestatements. 


Nested if statement

syntax:-

if(condition1)

{
  if(condition2)
  {
    ifstatement1;
    ifstatement2;
   }

}

The name nested if because an if statement inside another if statement.
In sted if statements if the condition1 satisfy it will check for condition2 and if it also satisfy then the if statements get executed. 

if else if statements

syntax:-

if(condition1)

{
 
    ifstatement1;
    ifstatement2;
 }
 elseif(condition2)
 {
  
    elseifstatement1;
    elseifstatement2;

}
else
{
    elsestatement1;
    elsestatement2;

}

In if elseif statement first condition1 in the if statement will check, 
if it is false then it will check condition2 if condition2 returns true the elseifstatents get executed ellse the else statements get executed.

switch statements

syntax:-

switch(expression)
{
  case caseconstant1:
                      statements;
                      break;
  case caseconstant2:
                      statements;
                      break;
  default:            
                      statements;
                      break;
}

Now let us explain the switch statement with an example;

int i=10
switch(i)
{
  case 5:
                      printf("In case 5");
                      break;
  case 10:
                      printf("In case 10");
                      break;
  default:            
                      printf("In default");
                      break;
}                 
                      

in this example the value of variable i is initialised as 10. And we are passing the variable i in the switch statement.
The output of the program will be, In case 10 because the case constant 10 matches with the expression inside the switch statement.

